segments.text: but I was naive enough that I didn't.
A fellow sat pretty close to me.
Ah, I see.
Other than that, I didn't know really what it was after.
Nobody ever tried to get any money from you or get you drunk?
Generally, you felt comfortable.
That's what I've heard over and over and over.
And you never used a sign...
to hold up with your destination?
And if you were going from here to Olney, what route did you take?
Could you do that in a day?
Most of the times we did it that day, a couple of times I spent a night someplace.
Let's see.
So you didn't eat, that freshman year, you didn't eat many meals on the campus?
No.
The only time that you ate is occasionally you'd go over the YMCA where they had a soda shop and you would just get a drink there or soda or something of the sort.
Do you remember how much money, spendable money, you had that first year?
Not very much.
Probably less than $50.
I calculated the entire cost of that first year was $325.
Tuition, clothes, meals.
Had your father given you any particular
part of a herd or acreage for you to work and save money from?
No, in my 4-H work, I was given...
Okay.
I bought cattle and things of this sort.
And so you saved from that?
I saved from that.
About how much did you have in your account?
Do you remember?
Oh, I think we had almost $600, $700, $800.
Oh.
Pretty much.
By today's standards, that's a good sum.
I do recall coming back the second semester of my sophomore year, I had to borrow from my brother's account.
I did not work.
While you were here?
While I was here.
I had no job.
Except the last year, I did have a small paying job.
Let's see, in terms of your freshman year,
as you now look back, what were the key academic classes that you took that freshman year and the impact they had on you?
The English class, classes, the course in agricultural economics had an impact because I began to learn the world.
Of course, I felt at home in the animal science class or animal husbandry class.
Mm-hmm.
probably I learned a great deal.
I'd say most of them, but probably the most impact course as I came along was a course in chemistry.
Who taught that?
Do you remember?
Was the instructor part of the impact?
The fellow whom for this fire is named after.
Not Isbell.
Not Texas, well, I don't know.
When did you begin to think about what your major was going to be?
At the outset.
Okay.
You had your mind made up?
I was going to be an animal husbandry major no matter what.
Okay, okay.
I came here with that idea.
I was going to be an animal husbandry major.
It never changed, except there was a bottle or two along the way, and I had some ideas that I had.
What did you think was the expected routine for going to class?
How did a student behave in class and so forth?
The expected routine was that you went to class.
It was never any thought of missing a class.
The only time that you missed a class was when you were ill or in a hospital or something of that sort where you just simply couldn't make it.
We walked into class, sat down, took notes, followed the instruction.
The instructor was it.
He knew everything.
And so that was where we were learning.
It's a duality of learning.
Right or wrong, yes or no, this is it.
Do you remember any incidents where someone went to sleep and what the instructor did?
Not until, not the freshman year.
Okay.
Go ahead to the others.
Well, sophomore year in chemistry class, the instructor was an interesting kind of a thing.
He'd throw chalk at the guy.
That...
freshman year you didn't have any problem passing your work?
Not at all.
I was distinguished both semesters.
I had a 2.25 waypoint ratio, a little better.
Under the old three-point.
And what did, what were your mom and dad's reaction to your work?
They were happy.
They were happy.
I don't think they were effusive, but they were happy.
They were happy to have me home in the summertime, and they were missing me.
Back home in the summer, what did you do?
Well, I helped my dad.
Worked on the farm.
Did you get paid?
No.
Did you get an allowance?
No.
I understand that fully.
That was the routine I had.
During your undergraduate years here, can you recall and share any jokes, prank, good bull that you either were part of or you observed?
Not really, no.
As I say, it was kind of a shock.
I need to tell you that during the sophomore year, I came back at the beginning of the sophomore year into Russell Hall,
was assigned to another unit called D Battery Field Artillery, which was a truck-drawn unit.
And I began to feel that if you were going to be on campus or be at Texas A&M University, you better associate yourself with the Corps.
So in the middle of the sophomore year, first semester of the sophomore year,
I moved into dormitories and stayed there all the way through.
Was there any reaction by the other sophomores?
Not really.
I think I was assigned a roommate that the others might have felt funny about.
But they didn't call you a frog or anything?
Didn't treat you like a transfer.
I had gone through a fish year.
I was fish couple the first year.
I was a sophomore and expected to do the hazing at the sophomores and to respond as a sophomore would.
And it was an integration, complete integration at the very outset.
Now, what dormitory were you in then, that second?
All right, and this is in, quote, the new dorm area.
The new dorm area.
But there were still, part of the Corps was still housed in the North Gate area?
No, then.
Oh, they were all down in the...
They were down then.
Oh, okay.
All right.
So now...
It didn't happen until the moving to the part of the Corps to the North Gate area did not come to the completion of the dormitories up here.
Okay.
Which was, what, 42?
Okay.
So now you were part of the entire Corps routine.
I was within it, and I came along and went through the ROTC situation.
Came back my seventh and eighth junior year, expecting to continue in the Corps and flunk the physical.
Really?
Yes.
I had what they would call a pilonidal cyst.

that I'd been born with and apparently this was this kind of discounted any officer being at it because it could become infected I never had any infection so I might say that during the Christmas holidays I went into Wichita Falls and had the thing cut out
and came back and by the end of the junior year I was in contract, but I ended up the following as a senior year with what is known as a one-button second lieutenant.
I lost all the, well I don't know whether my military career would have, or my military abilities would have sent me up along
But you remained in the Corps all four years.
In the same unit, D Battery Field Artillery.
I graduated out of D Battery Field Artillery.
And by far the majority of the student body was in the Corps all four years, weren't they?
Oh, I'd say yes, by far.
Well, everybody was in the Corps, with the exception of some graduate students.
were not in the Corps, even if you were physically unfit, you were still in the Corps.
They didn't have, I guess maybe they had what is equivalent to DNC today, but it was a ceremony, but you didn't know it.
That was a living quarters for students where that's where they had to be.
Your four years were from the fall of 39,
to January 43.
During those years, as you look back, please describe some of the memorable teachers, advisors, counselors that you recall, people that touched your life.
Well, it turned out that the one person that touched my life more, and I continue to touch it after I came back, was a teacher by the name of Paul Pearson.
and take a course in nutrition.
I liked it.
I had the chemistry, and I decided that maybe that I wanted to do this kind of thing.
Curiously, another professor that I enjoyed and had was Dr. John Miloff, veterinary medicine.
See, I decided that I wanted to be, possibly be, a veterinarian.
My parents put the kibosh to that.
You are not going to be a veterinarian.
We're going to pay for four years.
That's it.
You're on your own after that.
So I went to see Dean Marsteller and Dean Kyle.
And Dean Marsteller gave me permission to take the veterinary courses in the first year of veterinary medicine.
While you were still an undergraduate?
Junior year.
Were there many that got to do that?
As far as I know, I was the only one.
As far as I know, I'm not the only one to ever do that.
I don't know of any.
I've never heard of anyone else that did that.
That was, of course, the best year of my life because that essentially built the background upon which I built my graduate work
That's on to coming into the professorial positions and that sort.
All right, who were some others?
You mentioned a couple.
Who were some other faculty members that made a difference?
Bill Warren, John Riggs.
Bill Warren was there.
John Riggs, particularly.
You had to like him.
E.P.
Humbert.
That's a new name for me.
H-U-M-B-E-R-T. What did he do?
The head of the Department of Genetics.
And he took the beginning course in genetics.
Later on, John Quisenberry came into play, but took a course in animal breeding under him, in genetics.
P.W.
Williams.
He would later become...
He became acting president of the university and the Williams... Now, he was animal science?
He was animal science.
He was head of animal science.
Who were some characters you remember, character teachers, idiosyncrasies?
Snooks.
Who?
A fellow by the name of Snooks.
What did he teach, and why was he unusual?
He was unusual.
He'd come to class, and he'd turn the water on.
You see this water?
You don't touch it.
It's mine.
It's mine.
And he would write on the blackboard and then erase it immediately.
He would look out the window.
He was clearly a character.
Now, he's not the one that caught the student cheating with his watch, was it?
It could have been.
It could have been.
Somebody told me an incident about where the person teaching one of the big general chemistry courses, he thought he saw this student cheating on the final.
And so he goes out the back door, comes all the way around, walks up to the back of the student, and...
the student is looking at this watch, and he says, okay, stand up, I caught you.
Now stand up and read what you got on that watch.
And as the student thrust the watch in front of the faculty member, he read it, and it said, I fooled you this time, you old son of a bitch.
But this wasn't Snooks.
All right, who, some other, some other characters.
Some other characters.
That was bad.
Those were pretty reasonable people.
Let's see, the YMC, there was no MSC.
Describe what it provided for students.
I don't know what in particular it provided for students.
The only thing that I could see that it provided was a place where Lutherans could gather on campus.
Missouri Synod.
All right, and what did you, Missouri Synod Lutherans, when did you gather and what did you do?
We'd gather in the afternoons or we'd gather in the evenings or...
times we formed what is known as a club.
Then when they built the church in Bryan, some of us became members of that church.
Now, when you all got together, was it always religion that you talked about?
Not necessarily.
I'm sure other things such as football entered into the picture.
Were there some off-campus people that supported you?
Were there any key?

There was a fellow that I knew, the Reverend Henry Traubach, T-R-A-U-G-O-T-T, who was living at Curtin at the time, and he came in, and we did not have a Lutheran church, Missouri Synod, in either Bryan or College Station.
There was one in
another Lutheran church, but we had been taught so strictly that we thought that was a bunch of heretics.
Let's see, were the Kunze boys, did they overlap with you?
Yes.
And they were Missouri Synod?
George was a junior when I was a senior.
And he was Missouri Synod, was he not?
Missouri Synod.
Okay.
Let's see, MSC, Guyon Hall.
What do you remember that happened in Guyon Hall?
Oh, Guyon Hall was a wonderful place that we always had.
Town Hall it was called.
We all had tickets to Town Hall.
And all the programs, they were generally classic or semi-classical.
So this was music?
Do you remember any of the performers?
No, I don't.
What about, were there some notable speakers?
I don't recall any.
What about Religious Emphasis Week?
Was it held then?
I don't recall.
I don't think so.
Because I know it was after the war.
I don't know about before that.
Religious Emphasis Week.
Did you go to movies at Gine Hall?
We did movies at Gine Hall.
No, there was an assembly hall that movies had mostly.
More often we'd go into Bryan for movies.
Hitchhiking to Bryan.
Because you didn't have a car.
I didn't have a car.
Very few people had cars.
In fact, it was almost forbidden for students to have cars.
Mm-hmm.
Let's see, in Guyon Hall, did anybody ever create any mischief during a movie or a concert?
Oh, not during concerts, but during a movie occasionally we'd have somebody come up with a loud expletive.
Oh, okay, okay.
Do you remember any famous, during your undergraduate days, do you remember any famous visitors to the campus?
Don't remember any presidents or generals or anything like that.
Eisenhower came in.
I was not here when he came.
That's after the war.
The Secretary of Agriculture came in one time.
Henry Wallace?
No.
Let's see, football games.
1939 was a pretty good year for the Aggie football team.
It was a very good year.
I started football believing that Aggies couldn't lose.
Of course, the yell practice was held in front of the YMCA.
Describe a yell practice in those days.
Was it late on Friday evening?
Yes.
I don't know that it was a midnight Yale practice in the same sense.
But it was after dark?
After dark.
Did young ladies, if anybody had a date, did they take their date to Yale practice?
Yes.
They were always welcome.
They came down.
There were a few, but they were there.
And come in, either local ladies or TSCW.
And you all, on Saturday, the routine, was it similar to today in terms of marching into?
We all marched in, yes.
And did you?
We all marched in.
Of course, that was a student body.
And you stood and?
We stood.
During the first half and the second half and sat down during the... Did you have, during your undergraduate days, did you have a date for many games?
In my senior year, I had two or three dates for games.
And where were they from?
Local.
Currently, really, to be sure.
Okay, okay.
Did you do the court trips that year to the out-of-town games?
We went to court trips to Houston, Fort Worth, Dallas.
How did you... By train.
By train.
And where did you stay?
Um...
Usually in some hotel, basically.
It was never a particular problem or we moved in with somebody that we knew.
Somebody had a home there or stayed there or something of that sort.
Do you remember any major events for any of the Corps trips during your undergraduate days?
Was there any that you enjoyed more or far less than any of the others?
What was your favorite court trip?
My favorite court trip was always to Houston.
It was shorter and you could get by.
I had a roommate from Galveston.
So you'd go down there and stay with him?
Stay with him.
And you marched down Main Street?
Marched down whatever Main Street there was.
All right, like in Houston, Rice is a good distance from the middle of downtown.
How did the Corps get from the middle of downtown down to Rice Stadium?
You know, I was wondering about that.
I don't recall.
Because it's too far to walk.
I always had a ride or something, an automobile ride.
The reason why I don't remember is because it was never a problem, I guess.
Okay, okay.
While you were an undergraduate, what were the major student organizations on campus?
What student organizations had high prestige and
Well, it was an organization I did not know about.
But apparently a number of the students belonged to, particularly the military leaders in the Corps.
You're talking about one of the secret fraternities?
One of the secret fraternities.
As far as you know, or knew then,
Or as far as you know now about then, how many of those were there?
How many of those secret fraternities?
As far as I know, there was only one.
The TTs?
The TTs.
Two Texans.
Do you have any idea how many were in the TTs?
No idea.
I know I came across a situation and tried to come up with them and lost pretty heavily because of it.
That requires a bit of explanation.
Mm-hmm.
During my junior year, I decided that I was going to do, so I signed up with the Longhorn.
I became a staff member of the Longhorn.
The yearbook.
Yearbook.
And was one of the editors, or one of the staff people as far as yearbook was concerned.
And of course, I ran against the fellow who

finally became editor it was an election process for editor of the yearbook in 19 last year was there 1942 43 yearbook uh lost lost pretty heavily and it was a blow to my ego at that particular point and as far as you know then later on I learned that a lot of the people that were
running for office and things for all these people that were in the True Texan organization.
I was never there.
I was sort of an outsider then.
Maybe that's what I resented a little bit about my classmates as far as I'm concerned.
As far as I have been able to learn about the TTs and any other group, their primary purpose seems to have been to get their own members
into positions of student leadership.
That's right.
That's the best I can get.
That's the best I can get.
They did it.
And nobody knew exactly how many they were or where they met.
Is that right?
Let's see.
The key organizations, the band, which I was not a member of, obviously.
But was it?
Was it highly respected?
Was there even a student body president then?
There was a student body president, and he carried a great deal of prestige.
Of course, the other person was commander of the Corps.
What about Head Yellator?
The Yellators themselves were well-known, and I
I suspect admired.
They were all basically elected to the particular positions.
Senior class president, was that a highly sought position?
That was, I didn't seek it, but
nor did I seek any class offers as far as...
But I mean, in the hierarchy on the campus, was that...
Yes, it was.

It was one of the people that you began to remember, and as a result, a lot of these people who were leadership did become leaders after graduation, and you heard about them, both in the community and away.
So you got here as World War II is beginning.
Let's try to think about the effect of the war.
When did you first realize that that war that started September 1, 1939 might have an effect on your life?
Probably at the very beginning.
Because we all knew that the United States was going to get in it.
And I think when they passed the Selective Service Act is when you begin to realize that the best thing to do is to stay in Texas A&M and become part of the military there if you possibly could.
Did you and your buddies talk about the war much in your ordinary conversations?
No, we didn't, actually.
It was sort of a distant kind of thing.
course on December 5th in 1941.
Where were you when you heard that news?
I had just come back from a field trip out in the area for an agronomy soils course.
And as we drove up, there was a bunch of us in the back end of a truck, an open truck.
The campus was going wild at that particular point.
They shouted the Japanese had bombed Pearl Harbor.
That was the first we heard about it.
Did you know where Pearl Harbor was?
Yes.
Oh, you did?
Okay.
I was a sixth grader, and I didn't know.
Our teacher had to tell us.
We knew where Hawaii was, but we didn't know about Pearl Harbor.
Did you and your buddies listen on Monday, December 8th?
We were in the Dono, yes.
To the Roosevelt speech?
We were listening to the Roosevelt speech and the missiles.
What changes were there on campus soon after the war started?
Well, you suddenly, you knew where you were going to be, and this was December 41, and it became
to me, imperative to get that contract in order to stay in the military and not be pulled in as a... As a draftee?
As a draftee.
I don't think there was as much change in the campus as that, except that the planning began to change where we were going to go to school straight through.
We no longer had a...
The summer was going to disappear.
The 1943 class year started in June.
So that you started 12 months a year.
We started 12 months a year.
And did the semester length change?
Was it still September through the end of January, January through the end of May?
It was through the end of January.
Okay.
Probably, no, the semester length did not change.
Okay.
Nor did it juxtaposition.
So you just...
